---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const meta = {
  title: 'Webflow vs WordPress 2025: No-Code vs Open Source',
  description: 'Webflow: Visual builder, hosting included, from $14/month. WordPress: Free software, separate hosting needed, unlimited flexibility. Webflow is designer-friendly no-code. WordPress is powerful but complex. Choose Webflow for design control. WordPress for content-heavy sites.',
  image: '/og-image.svg',
  keywords: ['Webflow vs WordPress', 'website builder comparison', 'CMS comparison', 'no-code vs open source'],
};
---

<Layout {...meta}>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-[#4353FF]/5 to-[#0065FF]/5 py-12 sm:py-16 md:py-20">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4">
      <p class="text-[10px] sm:text-xs font-black text-[#4353FF] mb-4 tracking-[0.3em] uppercase">
        Website Builder Comparison · 2025
      </p>

      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-black mb-6 leading-tight">
        Webflow vs WordPress
      </h1>

      <p class="text-lg sm:text-xl md:text-2xl text-gray-700 mb-8">
        Webflow and WordPress represent two different approaches to building websites. Webflow is visual no-code for designers. WordPress is open-source CMS for everything. Webflow hosts for you. WordPress requires hosting. Webflow costs money but saves time. WordPress is free but costs time. Both work. Neither is universally better.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-white bg-opacity-50 border-2 border-gray-300 rounded-xl p-6">
        <p class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">
          Quick answer: Choose Webflow if you want visual design control without code. Hosting, security, updates included. Choose WordPress if you need unlimited flexibility, content management, or budget is tight. Webflow is faster to build but harder to migrate away. WordPress takes longer but you own everything.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Quick Comparison -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      Quick Comparison
    </h2>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="bg-gray-100">
            <th class="text-left p-4 font-bold">Feature</th>
            <th class="text-left p-4 font-bold">Webflow</th>
            <th class="text-left p-4 font-bold">WordPress</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">Ease of Use</td>
            <td class="p-4">Visual, designer-friendly</td>
            <td class="p-4">Dashboard, steeper learning curve</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b bg-gray-50">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">Hosting</td>
            <td class="p-4">Included</td>
            <td class="p-4">Self-hosted required</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">Flexibility</td>
            <td class="p-4">High within platform</td>
            <td class="p-4">Unlimited with plugins</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b bg-gray-50">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">CMS</td>
            <td class="p-4">Built-in, native</td>
            <td class="p-4">Plugin-based (varies)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">E-commerce</td>
            <td class="p-4">Built-in (additional cost)</td>
            <td class="p-4">WooCommerce plugin</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b bg-gray-50">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">Cost</td>
            <td class="p-4">$14+/month</td>
            <td class="p-4">Free + hosting cost</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">Ownership</td>
            <td class="p-4">Platform dependent</td>
            <td class="p-4">You own everything</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b bg-gray-50">
            <td class="p-4 font-bold">Best For</td>
            <td class="p-4">Design-first sites</td>
            <td class="p-4">Content-heavy sites</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Webflow Deep Dive -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      What Webflow Does Well
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Visual Design Control</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Webflow's visual editor gives designers pixel-perfect control without code.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Designers can build exactly what they envision. No fighting with templates or hiring developers. The visual canvas is intuitive for anyone with design experience.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Everything Included</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Hosting, SSL, security, backups, updates - all handled by Webflow.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> No technical maintenance required. You focus on building, not managing servers. WordPress requires constant updates, security patches, backup management. Webflow handles it all.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Native CMS</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Content management built into the platform from the start.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> CMS features like collections, dynamic pages, and filtering work seamlessly. WordPress plugins can be clunky. Webflow's CMS is native and polished.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Clean Code Export</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Export clean HTML, CSS, and JS if you ever need to leave.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> You're not completely locked in. Unlike Squarespace or Wix, Webflow lets you export code. Migration is possible if difficult.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Interactions and Animations</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Build complex animations and micro-interactions visually.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Creating polished interactions in WordPress requires coding. Webflow makes it visual and accessible to designers. Scroll effects, hover states, page transitions - all doable without code.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WordPress Deep Dive -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      What WordPress Does Well
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-purple-50 border-2 border-purple-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Unlimited Flexibility</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">60,000+ plugins mean you can build almost anything.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> If you can imagine it, there's probably a WordPress plugin for it. Webflow is constrained to its platform. WordPress is limited only by your patience for configuration.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-purple-50 border-2 border-purple-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Content Management Excellence</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">WordPress started as blogging software. Content management is in its DNA.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> For blogs, publications, content-heavy sites, WordPress excels. The editor, media management, and publishing workflow are mature and polished.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-purple-50 border-2 border-purple-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">You Own Everything</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">WordPress is open-source. You control your data, your site, your destiny.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Webflow could change pricing or features. You're at their mercy. WordPress is yours. You can host anywhere, customize anything, migrate anytime. No platform lock-in.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-purple-50 border-2 border-purple-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Massive Ecosystem</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Themes, plugins, developers, tutorials - WordPress has it all.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> If you need help, it's available. WordPress developers are everywhere. Webflow experts are fewer. The ecosystem means solutions exist for any problem.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-purple-50 border-2 border-purple-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">WooCommerce for E-commerce</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Powerful e-commerce through the most popular WordPress plugin.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> WooCommerce powers a huge portion of online stores. It's flexible, extensible, and free. Webflow's e-commerce costs extra and is less mature.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Pricing -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      Pricing Comparison
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Webflow Pricing</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• <strong>Starter:</strong> Free (2 sites, Webflow branding)</li>
          <li>• <strong>Basic:</strong> $14/month (custom domain, 2 sites)</li>
          <li>• <strong>CMS:</strong> $23/month (CMS features, 3 sites)</li>
          <li>• <strong>Business:</strong> $39/month (3 sites, more features)</li>
          <li>• <strong>E-commerce:</strong> Additional $29/month</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700"><strong>Hosting included:</strong> All plans include hosting and SSL.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-purple-50 border-2 border-purple-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">WordPress Pricing</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• <strong>Software:</strong> Free forever</li>
          <li>• <strong>Hosting:</strong> $3-50/month depending on needs</li>
          <li>• <strong>Premium themes:</strong> $30-200 each (optional)</li>
          <li>• <strong>Premium plugins:</strong> Varies (many free options)</li>
          <li>• <strong>Maintenance:</strong> Your time or hiring help</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700"><strong>Hidden cost:</strong> Your time managing updates, security, backups. Or paying someone to do it.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- When to Choose -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      When to Choose Each
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-green-50 border-2 border-green-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">✅ Choose Webflow If</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• <strong>You're a designer:</strong> Visual control is important to you</li>
          <li>• <strong>You want speed:</strong> Build faster without coding</li>
          <li>• <strong>You want included hosting:</strong> No server management</li>
          <li>• <strong>You need animations:</strong> Complex interactions without code</li>
          <li>• <strong>You have budget:</strong> Can afford monthly fees</li>
          <li>• <strong>Marketing sites:</strong> Brochure sites, portfolios, landing pages</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-green-50 border-2 border-green-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">✅ Choose WordPress If</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• <strong>You need flexibility:</strong> Want unlimited plugin options</li>
          <li>• <strong>You're blogging seriously:</strong> WordPress is content-first</li>
          <li>• <strong>Budget is tight:</strong> Can't afford monthly fees</li>
          <li>• <strong>You want ownership:</strong> Control your data and destiny</li>
          <li>• <strong>You need e-commerce:</strong> WooCommerce is mature and powerful</li>
          <li>• <strong>You have technical skills:</strong> Or budget to hire someone who does</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Bottom Line -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <div class="bg-white bg-opacity-50 border-2 border-gray-300 rounded-xl p-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-black mb-6">Bottom Line</h2>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">Webflow and WordPress both work. The choice depends on your priorities and skills. Webflow offers visual design with everything included. WordPress offers unlimited flexibility but requires maintenance.</p>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6"><strong>Choose Webflow for:</strong></p>
      <ul class="space-y-3 mb-6">
        <li>• Visual design control without code</li>
        <li>• Included hosting and maintenance</li>
        <li>• Faster build time for marketing sites</li>
        <li>• Native CMS and e-commerce</li>
        <li>• You have budget for monthly fees</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6"><strong>Choose WordPress for:</strong></p>
      <ul class="space-y-3 mb-6">
        <li>• Unlimited plugin flexibility</li>
        <li>• Content-heavy sites and blogs</li>
        <li>• Budget constraints (free software)</li>
        <li>• Complete ownership and control</li>
        <li>• Access to massive ecosystem</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700"><strong>Can't decide?</strong> Start with WordPress if budget is tight. Start with Webflow if design is priority and budget allows. Both offer trials or free ways to test before committing.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Related -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black mb-6 text-gray-900">
      Related Comparisons
    </h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <a href="/wix-vs-squarespace" class="block bg-gray-50 hover:bg-gray-100 rounded-lg p-6 transition-colors">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Wix vs Squarespace</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Popular no-code builders</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/framer-vs-squarespace" class="block bg-gray-50 hover:bg-gray-100 rounded-lg p-6 transition-colors">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Framer vs Squarespace</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Modern vs established</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
